## purpose
Defines the canonical architectural role of event in CivilizationOS.

## design_intent
Event is the bounded unit of meaningful change
that records that something happened,
who or what it affected,
when it occurred,
under which boundary it occurred,
and what downstream interpretation is allowed.

Event is not identical to state,
not identical to history,
and not identical to notification.
It is the governed change record
from which state transitions,
history accumulation,
and downstream reactions may derive.

## architectural_position
Event sits between:
- actor/entity activity
- state transition
- history accumulation
- integration exchange
- audit reconstruction
- replay and review flows

## required_behavior
- event identity must remain explicit
- event source must remain explicit
- event occurrence boundary must remain explicit
- event payload meaning must remain explicit
- current processing and historical retention must remain distinguishable
- replay and original occurrence must remain distinguishable

## canonical_rules
- event must not overwrite source truth by itself
- event occurrence and event interpretation must remain distinguishable
- replayed event must not pretend to be original occurrence
- current processing state and historical event state must remain distinguishable
- ambiguous event boundary fails closed

## state_model
The event domain distinguishes:
- proposed event
- accepted event
- recorded event
- processed event
- rejected event
- replayed event
- historical event

## actor_boundary
- source actor
- system recorder
- reviewer
- operator
- adapter

## decision_matrix
- if source identity is unclear, stop event acceptance
- if occurrence boundary is unclear, fail closed
- if payload exceeds declared meaning, route to denial or review
- if replay is requested, preserve replay distinction
- if historical reference is requested, preserve historical distinction

## review_checklist
- event identity is explicit
- source and occurrence are explicit
- replay distinction is explicit
- historical distinction is explicit
